⊢ seed
  given topic ≡ "compilers"
  yield questions[]

  ∴ Generate 3 interesting questions about «topic».

  ⊨ questions has exactly 3 entries
  ⊨ each question is about «topic»

⊢ explore
  given question
  yield answer, follow-ups[]

  ∴ Answer «question» in 2-3 sentences.
    Generate 0-2 follow-up questions that go deeper.

  ⊨ answer addresses «question»
  ⊨ follow-ups has 0-2 entries

⊢ spawn
  given seed→questions
  given §explore
  yield §new-cells[]

  ∴ For each question in «seed→questions», create a new
    instance of «§explore» with that question as input.
    Output the new cell definitions.

  ⊨ §new-cells has same length as «seed→questions»
  ⊨ each new cell is a copy of §explore with question bound

―――――――――――――――――――――――――――――――
Frontier at t0: [seed]
  seed executes → questions ≡ ["How do parsers work?", "What is an AST?", "What are optimization passes?"]

Frontier at t1: [spawn]
  spawn executes → §new-cells ≡ [
    ⊢ explore-1
      given question ≡ "How do parsers work?"
      yield answer, follow-ups[]
      ...
    ⊢ explore-2
      given question ≡ "What is an AST?"
      yield answer, follow-ups[]
      ...
    ⊢ explore-3
      given question ≡ "What are optimization passes?"
      yield answer, follow-ups[]
      ...
  ]

Frontier at t2: [explore-1, explore-2, explore-3]
  (all three are ready — parallel execution valid)
  explore-1 → answer, follow-ups ≡ ["How does recursive descent work?"]
  explore-2 → answer, follow-ups ≡ ["What are AST transformations?", "How do visitors work?"]
  explore-3 → answer, follow-ups ≡ []

Frontier at t3: new spawn from follow-ups → 3 more explore cells
  ...

THE FRONTIER GROWS. This is the semantic automata.
It never terminates unless follow-ups are always empty.
